<Base
  title="Genome browser integration — JBrowseMSA"
  description="Use react-msaview inside JBrowse 2 — an MSA viewer with a tree beside genome annotation, DNA-alignment tracks, and protein↔genome coordinate sync, driven entirely by declarative URLs."
  wide
>
  <article class="prose">
    <h1>In the genome browser</h1>
    <p>
      react-msaview ships as a JBrowse 2 plugin
      (<a href="https://github.com/GMOD/jbrowse-plugin-msaview">jbrowse-plugin-msaview</a>), so the
      same viewer — alignment, phylogenetic tree, and all — runs as a view <em>inside</em> JBrowse,
      stacked alongside a Linear Genome View with gene annotation and multiple-alignment tracks.
      Every view here is opened by a <strong>declarative link</strong>: the whole multi-view session
      lives in the URL, with nothing to install or set up.
    </p>

    <h2 id="linked-src">A linked protein view: SRC, beside its gene</h2>
    <p>
      The MSA viewer can also be <strong>connected</strong> to the genome view so the two share
      coordinates. This link opens the human <strong>SRC</strong> proto-oncogene on hg38 beside the
      Src-family kinase alignment, linked through the SRC transcript model so the mapping is a true
      protein-to-nucleotide one:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Click a residue in the alignment → the genome view navigates to that residue's codon.</li>
      <li>Hover the gene in the genome view → the corresponding alignment column highlights.</li>
    </ul>

    <figure>
      <a href={links.proteinLinked} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <img
          src={`${base}/media/genome-browser-src.png`}
          alt="JBrowse: the human SRC gene on hg38 above the Src-family kinase alignment and tree, connected as one view"
        />
      </a>
      <figcaption>
        The human SRC gene on hg38 (canonical RefSeq Select / MANE transcript) above the Src-family
        kinase alignment, connected through the SRC transcript model so residues and codons share
        coordinates.{' '}
        <a href={links.proteinLinked} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open this view in JBrowse ↗</a>
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2 id="braf-v600e">Zoomed on a mutation: BRAF V600E</h2>
    <p>
      The same connected pattern zoomed to a single codon: human <strong>BRAF</strong> beside the
      RAF-family kinase alignment, positioned on the <strong>V600</strong> codon with the matching
      alignment column pre-highlighted. <strong>V600E</strong> (<code>c.1799T&gt;A</code>) is the most
      common oncogenic mutation in melanoma; V600 is <strong>invariant</strong> down the RAF family, so
      the highlighted column is solid, and a <strong>ClinVar pathogenic-variant track</strong> stacks
      disease alleles directly onto the codon.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <a href={links.brafV600} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <img
          src={`${base}/media/genome-browser-braf-v600e.png`}
          alt="JBrowse: BRAF zoomed on the V600 codon with a ClinVar pathogenic-variant pileup above the lit, invariant V600 alignment column"
        />
      </a>
      <figcaption>
        BRAF zoomed on the <strong>V600</strong> codon — gene track (canonical transcript) and the
        ClinVar pathogenic-variant pileup above, the invariant V600 alignment column lit across the RAF
        family below. The highlighted genome base and alignment column are the same residue.{' '}
        <a href={links.brafV600} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open this view in JBrowse ↗</a>
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2 id="tp53-r248">Conservation meets pathogenicity: TP53 R248</h2>
    <p>
      A whole clinical archive landing on one conserved column: human <strong>TP53</strong> on hg38
      with a <strong>ClinVar pathogenic-variant track</strong>, beside p53 aligned across thirteen
      vertebrates, positioned on the <strong>R248</strong> codon — the most frequently mutated residue
      in TP53. A dense wall of ClinVar variants stacks on the codon while the alignment column reads
      <code>R</code> in every species: the pathogenic pileup and the conserved column are the same
      position.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <a href={links.tp53R248} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <img
          src={`${base}/media/genome-browser-tp53-r248.png`}
          alt="JBrowse: TP53 on the R248 codon with a dense ClinVar pathogenic-variant wall above the conserved R alignment column across vertebrates"
        />
      </a>
      <figcaption>
        TP53 on the <strong>R248</strong> codon — a dense wall of ClinVar pathogenic variants over the
        codon, above the alignment column that reads <code>R</code> in every vertebrate. The pathogenic
        pileup and the conserved column are the same position.{' '}
        <a href={links.tp53R248} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open this view in JBrowse ↗</a>
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2 id="tp53-protein3d">Into three dimensions: TP53, alignment, and structure</h2>
    <p>
      The same connection extends to the protein's <strong>3D structure</strong>. With
      <a href="https://github.com/GMOD/jbrowse-plugin-protein3d">jbrowse-plugin-protein3d</a> in the
      mix, one link opens <em>three</em> linked views — the human <strong>TP53</strong> gene (RefSeq +
      ClinVar), the p53 ortholog alignment, and the <strong>AlphaFold</strong> p53 structure — all
      connected to the same genome view, and all opened with a single annotated feature pinpointed
      across the three. Here it's the p53 <strong>nuclear export signal</strong> (UniProt motif,
      residues 339–350): magenta on the structure, a band over the gene, and the matching columns in
      the alignment — the same residues, located three ways at once.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <a href={links.tp53Protein3d} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <img
          src={`${base}/media/genome-browser-tp53-protein3d.png`}
          alt="JBrowse: TP53 gene with ClinVar, the p53 ortholog alignment, and the AlphaFold structure, all connected, with the nuclear export signal motif highlighted across genome, alignment, and 3D structure"
        />
      </a>
      <figcaption>
        Genome, alignment, and AlphaFold structure as one connected session, with the p53 nuclear
        export signal motif (UniProt P04637, residues 339–350) lit across all three — magenta in the
        structure, a highlight band over the gene, and the matching columns in the alignment. The whole
        layout, connections, and the pre-lit motif are declared in the URL.{' '}
        <a href={links.tp53Protein3d} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open this view in JBrowse ↗</a>
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2 id="how-built">How the links are built</h2>
    <p>
      Each link is a JBrowse
      <a href="https://jbrowse.org/jb2/docs/urlparams/#session-spec">session spec</a>
      (<code>?config=…&amp;session=spec-&#123;"views":[…]&#125;</code>), where each entry launches a
      <code>LinearGenomeView</code> or an <code>MsaView</code>. To <em>connect</em> the two, the genome
      view gets an <code>id</code> and the <code>MsaView</code> carries:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>connectedViewId</code> — the genome view's <code>id</code>.</li>
      <li><code>connectedFeature</code> — the transcript model that maps codons to residues.</li>
      <li><code>querySeqName</code> — the matching alignment row.</li>
      <li><code>highlightColumns</code> — seeds the lit-column overlay.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Transcript models and alignment/tree/ClinVar data are regenerated reproducibly from public
      sources by the scripts under <code>scripts/</code> (<code>src-protein-link</code>,
      <code>braf-protein-link</code>, <code>tp53-protein-link</code>). A view loaded from a
      cross-origin config asks you to trust the plugin once before it renders.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
